ral_normalized": false, "mention": "cyp17a1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9942479133605957, "span": {"begin": 409, "end": 416}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1583"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "cyp11c1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9938520193099976, "span": {"begin": 421, "end": 428}}, {"id": ["mesh:C016531"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "11KT", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9819048047065735, "span": {"begin": 475, "end": 479}}, {"id": ["mesh:C016531"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "11KT", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9926180243492126, "span": {"begin": 520, "end": 524}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "humans", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9932088255882263, "span": {"begin": 670, "end": 676}}, {"id": ["mesh:C016531"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "11KT", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9906265735626221, "span": {"begin": 678, "end": 682}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4683", "4830"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "&nbsp;", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.7024062871932983, "span": {"begin": 814, "end": 820}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:238"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "mettl3&nbsp;gene", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.7706785202026367, "span": {"begin": 820, "end": 836}}, {"id": ["mesh:D020964"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "embryonic lethality", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999925494194031, "span": {"begin": 851, "end": 870}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:7955"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "zebrafish", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9473738670349121, "span": {"begin": 958, "end": 967}}], "text": "11-ketotestosterone (11KT; CAS 564-35-2 |&nbsp;DTXSID8036499) is an oxygenated steroidal androgen with a keto group at the C11 position (Pretorius et al. 2017).&nbsp;  11-ketotestosterone is a&nbsp;dominant androgen in teleost fish (Borg 1994). It&nbsp;is synthesized from testosterone using the enzymes CYP11b1 and HSD11b (Yazawa et al., 2008;&nbsp;Swart et al., 2013).&nbsp;Zebrafish studies also show that cyp17a1 and cyp11c1 knockouts have dramatically reduced levels of 11KT (Shu et al., 2020; Zhang et al., 2020)  11KT is also produced by other vertebrates, although the site of its biosynthesis and physiological signficance in different taxa can vary widely. In humans, 11KT is primarily synthesized in the adrenal glands (Pretorius et al. 2017; Turcu et al. 2018).&nbsp;  &nbsp;  Although mutations in the&nbsp;mettl3&nbsp;gene usually cause embryonic lethality, one particular mutation in non-lethal and causes significantly reduced 11KT levels in zebrafish (Xia et al., 2018)", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:49:46 +0000 2026"}